&gt; Subject: [neat] 3D HyperNEAT Substrates
&gt; 
&gt; Hi,
&gt; 
&gt; Not sure if this has been discussed but I was thinking of implementing 3D
&gt; substrates. The canonical HyperNEAT substrate I think is nodes arranged in
&gt; layers of lines on the cartesian plane, with each row having a distinct
&gt; position on the y-axis and the nodes within that row arranged along the
&gt; x-axis. Hence the strength of a connection is a function of all four
coords,
&gt; weight = f(x1,y1,x2,y2).
&gt; 
&gt; Seems to me that many common tasks (such as processing image data) require
&gt; each layer to be a plane, so we could have nodes in a plane occupying x/y
axes
&gt; and the planes/layers being distinguished by the z axis. weight =
&gt; f(x1,y1,z1,x2,y2,z2) and the original &#39;flat&#39; substrate can still be
&gt; represented if necessary.
&gt; 
&gt; I&#39;m intending to implement it like this - has anyone else implemented
CPPNs
&gt; this way? Are there any problems with this approach?
&gt; 
&gt; Thanks,
&gt; 
&gt; Colin.
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; 




